Build a single-page concept prototype called RoomCraft Concept Test.

The goal is simple: prove whether uploading a real room photo, marking the usable floor area, and dragging furniture into the room feels intuitive and visually convincing.

This is NOT a production app. No backend, no database, no auth, no AI APIs, no payments, no dashboards. Everything must run client-side only.

Stack:
React + TypeScript + Konva.js / react-konva.

Core idea:
Take a photo of your room. Mark the floor area like a document scanner frame. Enter the real room dimensions. Add furniture items. See the furniture footprint, item dimensions, and room dimensions clearly.

Important UX inspiration:
The floor-marking experience should be inspired by document scanner apps, like the way DocScan / mobile scanner apps let users adjust a detected document frame after taking a photo.

Use that same mental model here, but for a room floor:

- The user uploads a room photo
- The app shows a four-corner adjustable frame
- The user drags each corner to match the visible floor area
- The frame feels like correcting a scanned document crop
- The frame has clear corner handles, a shaded overlay, and a dashed outline
- The user can easily confirm or readjust it

Do not copy any specific app branding, icons, or exact UI. Only borrow the interaction pattern: a clean, draggable, four-point scanner-style frame.

════════════════════════════════════
APP STRUCTURE
════════════════════════════════════

The entire app should be one screen.

Main sections:

1. Room photo upload
2. Floor frame / room dimension setup
3. Furniture placement canvas
4. Furniture catalog / custom item input

No routing. No login. No backend.

Use a simple 3-step flow shown clearly in the UI:

1. Upload room photo
2. Mark floor + enter room size
3. Add furniture

The user should always know what step they are in.

════════════════════════════════════
1. PHOTO UPLOAD
════════════════════════════════════

Create a simple upload area:

- File input or drag-and-drop
- accept="image/*"
- Read the image locally using FileReader
- Store the image in React state only
- Display it immediately as the canvas background
- Do not upload or save the image anywhere

After upload, move the user directly into floor setup.

Do not ask for room type, style, account, onboarding questions, or anything extra.

════════════════════════════════════
2. FLOOR FRAME INSPIRED BY DOCUMENT SCANNER APPS
════════════════════════════════════

After the room photo is uploaded, show a draggable floor frame inspired by document scanner apps. Instead of detecting a paper document, the user is marking the visible floor area of the room. The experience should feel familiar: like adjusting the corners of a scanned document before saving it.

The frame should behave like a scanner crop frame:

- Four draggable corner points
- Semi-transparent polygon overlay
- Gold dashed outline
- Clear corner handles
- User can drag corners to match the visible floor area
- This floor frame represents the real usable floor space

Important:
Do NOT use this floor frame for furniture items. This frame is only for the room/floor.

Add a clear step title:

"Mark your floor area"

Add short helper text:

"Drag the corners to match the floor area in your room photo."

Room dimension input:

Ask the user to enter the real dimensions of the marked floor area:

- Room width
- Room depth
- Optional room height
- Unit selector: cm, m, inches, feet

Example:
Width: 4.5 m
Depth: 3.2 m
Height: 2.7 m

Show the selected unit everywhere.

Once dimensions are entered, display dimension labels directly on the floor frame:

- Width label on the front/back floor edge
- Depth label on the side floor edge
- Optional room height shown as a small vertical ruler on the side

Add buttons:

- Confirm floor
- Redraw / adjust floor
- Skip floor setup and place freely

After confirming, move into furniture placement mode.

════════════════════════════════════
3. FURNITURE CATALOG
════════════════════════════════════

Hardcode around 10 furniture items directly in code.

Example categories:

- Sofas
- Chairs
- Tables
- Rugs
- Lighting
- Storage
- Decor

Each furniture item should include:

- id
- name
- category
- width
- depth
- height
- unit
- imageUrl
- price optional

Use simple public image URLs or local placeholder assets. Clean-ish backgrounds are fine. Do not over-engineer background removal.

Display furniture in a horizontal bottom strip or right sidebar.

Each item card should show:

- Thumbnail
- Name
- Width x Depth x Height
- Add button

